<activity xml:id="act-PolynomialDivision">
    <title>Polynomial Division</title>
    <introduction>
        <p>
            We're going to do some fiddling with polynomials, and hopefully use this as a bridge to connect how we think of polynomials and power series with how we think about our traditional infinite series and the notions of convergence that we've already built.
        </p>
    </introduction>
    <task>
        <statement>
            <p>
                We're going to factor some polynomials, but we might end up using some division. First, we'll confirm some factors that we already know. 
                <me>
                    x^2-1 = (x-1)(x+1)
                </me>
                We'll confirm this by using division.
                <tabular>
                    <row halign="right">
                    <cell></cell>
                    <cell bottom="medium"></cell>
                    <cell bottom="medium"></cell>
                    <cell bottom="medium"></cell>
                    </row>
                    <row halign="right">
                    <cell right="medium"><m>x-1</m></cell>
                    <cell><m>x^2</m></cell>
                    <cell><m></m></cell>
                    <cell><m>-1</m></cell>
                    </row>
                </tabular>
            </p>
        </statement>
    </task>
    <task>
        <statement>
            <p>
                Now let's factor <m>x^3-1</m>. If the factors for this polynomial isn't as familiar, it might be helpful to know that <m>(x-1)</m> is also a factor of <m>x^3-1</m>.
                <tabular>
                    <row halign="right">
                    <cell></cell>
                    <cell bottom="medium"></cell>
                    <cell bottom="medium"></cell>
                    <cell bottom="medium"></cell>
                    <cell bottom="medium"></cell>
                    </row>
                    <row halign="right">
                    <cell right="medium"><m>x-1</m></cell>
                    <cell><m>x^3</m></cell>
                    <cell><m></m></cell>
                    <cell><m></m></cell>
                    <cell><m>-1</m></cell>
                    </row>
                </tabular>
            </p>
        </statement>
    </task>
    <task>
        <statement>
            <p>
                Let's try another one. Complete the following division.
                <tabular>
                    <row halign="right">
                    <cell></cell>
                    <cell bottom="medium"></cell>
                    <cell bottom="medium"></cell>
                    <cell bottom="medium"></cell>
                    <cell bottom="medium"></cell>
                    <cell bottom="medium"></cell>
                    </row>
                    <row halign="right">
                    <cell right="medium"><m>x-1</m></cell>
                    <cell><m>x^4</m></cell>
                    <cell><m></m></cell>
                    <cell><m></m></cell>
                    <cell><m></m></cell>
                    <cell><m>-1</m></cell>
                    </row>
                </tabular>
            </p>
        </statement>
    </task>
    <task>
        <statement>
            <p>
                Can you generalize this? Find the formula for <m>\dfrac{x^n-1}{x-1}</m> for some positive integer <m>n</m>.
                <tabular>
                    <row halign="right">
                    <cell></cell>
                    <cell bottom="medium"></cell>
                    <cell bottom="medium"></cell>
                    <cell bottom="medium"></cell>
                    <cell bottom="medium"></cell>
                    <cell bottom="medium"></cell>
                    </row>
                    <row halign="right">
                    <cell right="medium"><m>x-1</m></cell>
                    <cell><m>x^n</m></cell>
                    <cell><m></m></cell>
                    <cell><m></m></cell>
                    <cell><m></m></cell>
                    <cell><m>-1</m></cell>
                    </row>
                </tabular>
            </p>
        </statement>
    </task>
    <task>
        <statement>
            <p>
                Now that we have good evidence that
                <me>
                    \sum_{k=0}^\infty x^k = \frac{x^n-1}{x-1}
                </me>,
                We can apply a limit as <m>n\to\infty</m>. 
                <md>
                    <mrow> \sum_{k=0}^\infty x^k \amp =\lim_{n\to\infty} \sum_{k=0}^n x^k </mrow>
                    <mrow> \amp = \lim_{n\to\infty} \frac{x^n-1}{x-1}</mrow>
                </md> 
                For what values of <m>x</m> will this limit exist?
            </p>
        </statement>
    </task>
    <task>
        <statement>
            <p>
                Revisit <xref ref="thm-GeometricSeries" text="type-global-title"/>. Is there any difference for what we've just done compared to this result that we already know?
            </p>
        </statement>
    </task>
</activity>